ðŸ§  Soft Skills
Research on Pseudo-Classes in <a> Tags
Objective:
To explore the functionality and use cases of CSS pseudo-classes in styling <a> tags for enhanced user interaction.

Overview of Pseudo-Classes:

:Targets all unvisited links.

a:link {
  color: blue;
}
: Styles links that have already been visited.
css
Copy code
a:visited {
  color: purple;
}
: Applies styles when the mouse hovers over a link.
a:hover {
  color: red;
  text-decoration: underline;
}
: Applies styles when a link is being activated by the user.

a:active {
  color: green;
}
: Styles elements when they are in focus.

a:focus {
  outline: 2px solid orange;
}
## Use Cases
Content-Rich Websites (e.g., Wikipedia):
Uses pseudo-classes to distinguish between visited and unvisited links for easier navigation.
Login and Signup Forms:
Uses :focus to highlight the input fields when a user interacts with them.
Conclusion:
CSS pseudo-classes offer powerful ways to enhance the interactivity of links within a webpage. By applying different styles based on user interaction, developers can create a more engaging and intuitive browsing experience.

## Summary
In this session, the focus was on creating an interactive webpage using CSS pseudo-classes for <a> tags to improve user interaction. This included understanding the behavior of different pseudo-classes like :link, :visited, :hover, :active, and :focus, and their impact on the overall user experience of a webpage.
